### LINQ with Lambda Expressions

Lambda expressions are the foundation of LINQ method syntax. They provide concise, inline function definitions.

### Lambda Basics in LINQ

```csharp
// Full lambda syntax
numbers.Where((int n) => { return n > 5; });

// Simplified
numbers.Where(n => n > 5);
numbers.Select(n => n * n);
```

### Common LINQ Lambda Patterns

```csharp
var people = new List<Person>
{
    new Person { Name = "Alice", Age = 30, Salary = 50000 },
    new Person { Name = "Bob", Age = 25, Salary = 40000 },
    new Person { Name = "Charlie", Age = 35, Salary = 60000 }
};

// Filter with complex condition
var result = people.Where(p => p.Age >= 30 && p.Salary > 45000);

// Projection with anonymous type
var projected = people.Select(p => new { p.Name, Bonus = p.Salary * 0.1 });

// Sorting with lambda
var sorted = people.OrderByDescending(p => p.Salary).ThenBy(p => p.Name);
```

### Lambda with Index

```csharp
string[] fruits = { "Apple", "Banana", "Cherry" };

// Index parameter in Where and Select
var indexed = fruits.Select((fruit, index) => $"{index + 1}. {fruit}");
var filtered = fruits.Where((fruit, index) => index % 2 == 0);
```

### Aggregation with Lambda

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };

// Custom aggregation
int product = numbers.Aggregate((acc, n) => acc * n);  // 120

// Aggregate with seed
int factorial = numbers.Aggregate(1, (acc, n) => acc * n);  // 120

// Running total
var runningTotal = numbers.Select((n, i) => numbers.Take(i + 1).Sum());
```

### Complex Grouping

```csharp
var grouped = people
    .GroupBy(p => new { 
        p.Age / 10 * 10,  // Group by decade
        p.Name[0]          // Group by first letter
    })
    .Select(g => new { 
        Decade = g.Key, 
        Count = g.Count(),
        People = g.Select(p => p.Name)
    });
```

### Lambda Performance

| Aspect | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| Inlined lambdas | Compiled to delegate instances |
| Captured variables | Closure allocation overhead |
| Static lambdas | No closure (C# 9+ static lambda) |
| Deferred execution | Lambda runs per element during iteration |

### Static Anonymous Functions (C# 9+)

Prevent accidental captures:

```csharp
int threshold = 5;
var result = numbers.Where(static n => n > 0);  // Can't capture threshold
// var result = numbers.Where(n => n > threshold);  // Can capture
```

> **Key Point:** Lambda expressions are the primary way to express LINQ queries in method syntax. They can capture variables (closures) from the enclosing scope. Use lambdas for filter conditions, projections, sorting keys, and custom aggregations.

### Common Lambda Mistakes

```csharp
// Bad - unintended closure
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
    tasks.Add(Task.Run(() => Console.WriteLine(i)));  // All print 10

// Fix - capture loop variable
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
{
    int captured = i;
    tasks.Add(Task.Run(() => Console.WriteLine(captured)));
}

